1. Launch an EC2 instance
Use the Amazon Linux 2023 AMI (ami-06971c49acd687c30) in the us-east-2 region.

Choose t2.micro instance type (eligible for free tier).

Assign an existing key pair (my-key) or create a new one to enable SSH access.

Ensure the instance is launched in the correct VPC (vpc-05b94ec799e0933d5) and subnet (subnet-045209cbecc2c2dfc).

Configure security groups to allow:

SSH (TCP port 22) from your IP

HTTP (TCP port 80) from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)

2. Connect to your instance
Open a terminal or Git Bash and run:

bash
Copy
Edit
chmod 400 /path/to/my-key.pem
ssh -i "/path/to/my-key.pem" ec2-user@<public-ip-address>
Replace /path/to/my-key.pem with your private key path and <public-ip-address> with your EC2 instance’s public IPv4 address (e.g., 3.140.197.242).

3. Update packages on your instance
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo dnf update -y
4. Verify connectivity and instance info
Confirm instance is running and accessible.

Check instance details like AMI, instance type, and public IP:

bash
Copy
